courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
1. Understand the commonly used audiological tests and the various purposes that the tests may serve;
2. Describe the communication, language, speech and literacy characteristics of the individuals with hearing impairment;
3. Understand the critical concepts in speech perception assessments and aural (re)habilitation approaches across the age range.

By the completion of this course, students are expected to:

* identify relevant clinical , social, cultural and ethical issues related to complex cases in speech-language pathology;
* demonstrate entry-level clinical decision making by utilizing various clinical decision-making models while integrating clinical, ehtical and professional practice principles for complex cases;
* develop entry-level assessment and treatment plans for complex cases with communication and/or swallowing needs.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
1. Understand how theories could be integrated into clinical practice;
2. Systematically evaluate how a professional could manage clients with various communication disorders;
3. Manage clients with various communication and swallowing disorders under supervision

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
1. Classify speech sounds according to articulatory criteria;
2. Use phonetic transcription to learn the pronunciation of new words;
3. Recognize and analyze the phonological structure of the word;
4. Be able to apply the phonological concepts into data analysis
